text: Photo: Cliff Owen, AP FILE - In this Sept. 4, 2015, file photo, House Select Committee on Benghazi Chairman Trey Gowdy, R-S.C., talks with the media on Capitol Hill in Washington. WASHINGTON (AP) — The deadly 2012 attack on a U.S. compound in Benghazi, Libya, moves to the forefront of the presidential race when Democratic front-runner Hillary Rodham Clinton testifies Thursday before a Republican-led House committee.
